commitResults.messageTitle: Add CommandParser class + corresponding test class
commitResults.messageBody:
We need a CommandParser class to interpret the command and run the
right methods after that.

Having a class with all these methods together allow for more
organized code and easier debugging, as all the code relevant to
this functionality is in the same class.

Let's create a CommandParser class that consolidates all the
methods required for interpreting the incoming commands and running
the appropriate methods from other classes.

The Gradle check is not passing.

The Javadoc comment are dangling, as the methods have been
commented out. This is because the other classes required in the
CommandParser class have not been implemented yet.

Let's change the Javadoc comment to a standard comment temporarily,
and check if Gradle accepts it.

We need a way to take the user input and convert it into
information that the parser can understand.

These methods will help to isolate the command portion of the user
input and allow for easier calling of the appropriate commands
later.

Let's,
* create a few methods to split up the user input into the
command portion and the information portion.
* EXTRA: remove irrelevant files that were mistakenly committed
and merged.

commitResults.messageTitle: Implement command calling from other classes
commitResults.messageBody:
The methods in the other system classes cannot be called from the
main BusynessManager class.

We need to connect the BusynessManager class to the methods in
other system classes for BusynessManager to perform its tasks and
functions.

Let's create some methods in the parser to take in the command
from the user input, decide on what the command is, and run the
appropriate method from the other system classes.

The Gradle check is not passing.

The import statement was mistakenly added to the code.

Let's remove the import statement, and check if Gradle accepts
it.

The parser may perform unexpectedly when given the wrong inputs.
When an error occurs, the user may not be able to understand
what went wrong if we use the existing exceptions.

Adding custom exceptions will allow users to immediately
understand the mistake they made when providing input. Thus, they
will be able to correct their mistakes more quickly, instead
of trying to find out what actually went wrong.

Let's introduce some custom exceptions such as:
* InvalidString for when the user inputs an invalid String.
* InvalidCommand for when the command format is not followed.

commitResults.messageTitle: Create CommandParser class and corresponding test class
commitResults.messageBody:
Add CommandParser class + corresponding test class

We need a CommandParser class to interpret the command and run the right methods after that.

Having a class with all these methods together allow for more organized code and easier debugging, as all the code relevant to this functionality is in the same class.

Let's create a CommandParser class that consolidates all the methods required for interpreting the incoming commands and running the appropriate methods from other classes.

Implement user input interpretation

We need a way to take the user input and convert it into information that the parser can understand.

These methods will help to isolate the command portion of the user input and allow for easier calling of the appropriate commands later.

Let's,
* create a few methods to split up the user input into the command portion and the information portion.
* EXTRA: remove irrelevant files that were mistakenly committed and merged.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add proper command calling from other classes
commitResults.messageBody:
Implement command calling from other classes

The methods in the other system classes cannot be called from the main BusynessManager class.

We need to connect the BusynessManager class to the methods in other system classes for BusynessManager to perform its tasks and functions.

Let's create some methods in the parser to take in the command from the user input, decide on what the command is, and run the appropriate method from the other system classes.

Add custom exceptions

The parser may perform unexpectedly when given the wrong inputs. When an error occurs, the user may not be able to understand what went wrong if we use the existing exceptions.

Adding custom exceptions will allow users to immediately understand the mistake they made when providing input. Thus, they will be able to correct their mistakes more quickly, instead of trying to find out what actually went wrong.

Let's introduce some custom exceptions such as:

* InvalidString for when the user inputs an invalid String.
* InvalidCommand for when the command format is not followed.

commitResults.messageTitle: Modify JUnit tests and adjust extract method
commitResults.messageBody:
Some JUnit tests are not tailored towards the possible inputs from
the user. Moreover, once the tests are modified, the method for
extracting information does not work properly, as the actual output
differs from the expected output.

Focusing the tests on possible inputs can help to check on more
specific bugs that are more likely to occur during user input.

Let's
* edit the JUnit tests with possible command inputs instead of
more general ones.
* modify extractInfo() to fix the wrong output bug.

commitResults.messageTitle: Modify command extraction method + Edit JUnit tests
commitResults.messageBody:
The command extraction does not work for single-word user inputs.
Moreover, the JUnit tests are not as organized as desired.

Fixing the command extraction will expand the range of usability to
encompass single-word user inputs that do not contain any information.
Organising the JUnit tests will help to clarify the different
scenarios that the methods can face.

Let's,
* Fix extractCommand() to get single-word user inputs working.
* Organise the JUnit tests for better clarity.

commitResults.messageTitle: Rename custom exceptions and modify InvalidStringException
commitResults.messageBody:
The custom exceptions are not named as exceptions. Moreover, the
message printed in InvalidString is repeated in all scenarios.

Adding the word "Exception" to the custom exceptions will
explicitly inform others that they are exceptions. Removing the
message parameter will help to simplify the code.

Let's,
* Rename all custom exceptions and their class files to include
the word "Exception"
* Modify InvalidString such that there is no more message
parameter in the constructor.

commitResults.messageTitle: Implement exception handling for command interpretation
commitResults.messageBody:
The command interpretation methods do not contain any exception
handling.

Adding exceptions and handling them will allow the methods to end
in a controlled manner when incorrect parameters are given to them,
thereby protecting them from failing unexpectedly.

Let's,
* Modify the command interpretation methods to check for incorrect
inputs, and throw exceptions when necessary.
* Edit the main parsing method to catch any exception thrown.
* Add JUnit tests for scenarios when exceptions are thrown.
* Modify a few JUnit tests for correct format, but invalid user
inputs.
* EXTRA: add a Javadoc comment for the CommandParser class.
(because I forgot)

commitResults.messageTitle: Modify access levels for command interpretation methods
commitResults.messageBody:
The command interpretation methods currently have a public access
level.

Changing the access levels to a more restrictive level will help to
prevent incorrect and potentially destructive usage.

Let's modify the access levels for these methods to protected, so
that we can still run JUnit tests on them.

commitResults.messageTitle: Implement JUnit tests for command calling methods
commitResults.messageBody:
There are no methods to test the exception handling of the command
calling methods.

Creating methods to test the exception handling will help to
assure that the exception handling is working as expected.

Let's
* Add JUnit tests for situations when exceptions are thrown
from command calling methods.
* Modify the exception handling slightly for the JUnit tests to
work.
* Modify the method name of a few JUnit tests due to incorrect
naming conventions.
* Modify a few JUnit tests for converting a String to a number.

The code utilising the other classes are commented out, as these

Integrating them into the code will allow these classes to be

Keeping the indentation and Javadoc comment content consistent will

commitResults.messageTitle: Organise classes into packages and create JUnit test classes
commitResults.messageBody:
The classes used by BusynessManager are all in the main package.
Moreover, some of these classes do not contain JUnit tests.

Putting the classes into separate packages will help with keeping
the code organised and systematic. Implementing JUnit tests will
help to test the code for unexpected issues, thereby increasing
reliability.

Let's
* organise the different classes in BusynessManager into related
packages.
* create JUnit test classes for the classes in the main folder.
